  <!-- LEAD -->
  <p class="art-lead">
    Somewhere between the meal-prep spreadsheets, the 5am workout commitments, and the color-coded supplement schedules, a lot of people quietly give up. Not because they lack willpower — but because the plan was never realistic in the first place. And a growing body of research suggests they may have been right to walk away.
  </p>

  <p>
    The wellness industry has a complexity problem. Over the past two decades, the standard advice for improving health has become increasingly elaborate — more tracking, more restriction, more optimization. And yet, by almost every measurable population-level metric, people are not getting healthier. Chronic fatigue, stubborn weight, poor sleep, and low energy remain widespread — even among people who are actively trying.
  </p>

  <p>
    The explanation, according to behavioral researchers and habit scientists, may be simpler than we think: <strong>most people abandon complicated wellness plans not because of laziness, but because complexity is biologically unsustainable.</strong> The human brain is not built for indefinite willpower-intensive effort. It is built for routine, repetition, and low-friction behavior.
  </p>

