  <h2 class="sec-head">🧠 Why Complicated Plans Fail — The Science of Willpower Depletion</h2>

  <p>
    For decades, willpower was treated as a personal character trait — something you either had or you didn't. People who failed at diet plans were told they simply lacked discipline. But the scientific picture that emerged through the 2000s and 2010s reframed the entire conversation.
  </p>

  <p>
    Research from Roy Baumeister and colleagues introduced the concept of <strong>ego depletion</strong> — the idea that self-regulatory resources are finite. Every decision, every moment of restraint, every time you override an impulse draws from the same cognitive pool. A wellness plan that requires constant decision-making — tracking macros, deciding between approved and unapproved foods, timing supplements, scheduling workouts — depletes this pool rapidly. And when it's depleted, habits collapse.
  </p>

  <div class="pull-quote">
    <p>"The most successful long-term health behaviors are those that require the least ongoing conscious effort. Simplicity is not a shortcut — it is a prerequisite for sustainability."</p>
    <cite>— Journal of Health Psychology, Behavioral Sustainability Review, 2024</cite>
  </div>

  <p>
    This is why people who seem highly motivated at the start of a wellness plan are often the most likely to burn out. High motivation drives high complexity — and high complexity drives eventual abandonment. The most sustainable wellness behaviors, by contrast, tend to be almost boringly simple.
  </p>

