  <p>
    Recognizing these patterns is not a reason for shame. It is diagnostic information. A plan that requires more willpower than you can sustain is not a personal failure — it is a design failure.
  </p>

  <!-- SECTION 2 -->
  <h2 class="sec-head">🔄 What "Simple" Actually Means — And What It Doesn't</h2>

  <p>
    Simple does not mean effortless. And it does not mean doing nothing. What it means, in the context of sustainable wellness, is <strong>reducing the number of decisions, the cognitive load, and the friction involved in healthy behavior</strong> — so that those behaviors can persist even on difficult days, under stress, or during busy periods.
  </p>

  <p>
    The research literature on habit formation — particularly the work of James Clear, BJ Fogg, and Wendy Wood — converges on the same principle: <em>behavior change that sticks is behavior change that becomes automatic.</em> And automaticity requires repetition in a consistent context. Which means the same action, at the same time, in the same sequence — until the brain no longer needs to consciously initiate it.
  </p>

  <div class="sci-block">
    <strong>📋 The Habit Loop: Why Simple Routines Become Self-Sustaining</strong>
    Every habit operates on a three-part loop: cue → routine → reward. When the routine is simple enough to execute automatically after the cue, the brain begins encoding it in the basal ganglia — the region responsible for automatic behavior. Once encoded, the habit persists without conscious effort. Complexity disrupts this encoding process because it keeps behavior in the prefrontal cortex — where willpower lives — rather than allowing it to migrate to automated neural pathways.
  </div>

  <!-- SECTION 3 — The 5 Principles -->
